 at the posterior aspect of the skull. This landmark is important in the study of cranial anatomy and is used as a reference point in various medical and anthropological contexts.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECoronal and temporal\u003C/strong\u003E - These sutures do not meet at the lambda\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETemporal and sagittal\u003C/strong\u003E - These sutures do not meet at the lambda\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECoronal and sagittal\u003C/strong\u003E - These sutures meet at the bregma, not the lambda\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETemporal and lambdoid\u003C/strong\u003E - These sutures do not meet at the lambda\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The lambda is a major landmark on the skull where the sagittal and lambdoid sutures meet.","The lambda is located at the posterior aspect of the skull."],"references":["Singh, V. (2023). Textbook of Anatomy-Head, Neck and Brain, Volume III-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Patestas, M. A., \u0026 Gartner, L. P. (2016). A textbook of neuroanatomy. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Patel, C. R., Fernandez-Miranda, J. C., Wang, W. H., \u0026 Wang, E. W. (2016). Skull Base Anatomy. Otolaryngologic clinics of North America, 49(1), 9\u201320. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.otc.2015.09.001","Anderson, B. W., Kortz, M. W., Black, A. C., \u0026 Al Kharazi, K. A. (2023). Anatomy, Head and Neck, Skull. In StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58466"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17948"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58466","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/58466"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-23T00:17:13+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-23T00:18:28+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{